const CHEMISTRY_OCR_B_PRACTICE = {
  'S1': {
    name: 'Foundations of Chemistry',
    questions: [
      { q: 'Define the term relative atomic mass.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The weighted mean mass of an atom of an element (1 mark) compared to 1/12 of the mass of a carbon-12 atom (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State the number of protons, neutrons, and electrons in an atom of potassium-39.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Protons = 19, Neutrons = 20 (1 mark for both). Electrons = 19 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Write the electron configuration of a chlorine atom (Z=17).', marks: 1, markScheme: '1s2 2s2 2p6 3s2 3p5 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Calculate the number of moles in 3.01 x 10^23 molecules of water.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'n = 3.01 x 10^23 / 6.022 x 10^23 = 0.5 mol (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Define the term first ionisation energy.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'The energy required to remove one electron (1 mark) from each atom in one mole of gaseous atoms (1 mark) to form one mole of gaseous 1+ ions (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why sodium chloride has a high melting point.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'NaCl has a giant ionic lattice structure (1 mark). There are strong electrostatic attractions between oppositely charged Na+ and Cl- ions (1 mark). A large amount of energy is required to overcome these strong ionic bonds (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Draw a dot-and-cross diagram for ammonia (NH3).', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Three bonding pairs between N and each H shown correctly (1 mark). One lone pair on the nitrogen shown (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why the bond angle in water (104.5 degrees) is less than in methane (109.5 degrees).', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Water has two bonding pairs and two lone pairs (1 mark). Lone pairs repel more strongly than bonding pairs (1 mark). This greater repulsion compresses the bond angle below the tetrahedral angle (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Calculate the empirical formula of a compound containing 52.2% carbon, 13.0% hydrogen, and 34.8% oxygen by mass.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Divide by Ar: C = 52.2/12 = 4.35, H = 13.0/1 = 13.0, O = 34.8/16 = 2.175 (1 mark). Divide by smallest (2.175): C = 2, H = 5.98, O = 1 (1 mark). Empirical formula = C2H6O (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by a covalent bond.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A shared pair of electrons (1 mark) between two atoms, where both atoms contribute one electron to the bond (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State and explain the trend in atomic radius across Period 3.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Atomic radius decreases across Period 3 (1 mark). Nuclear charge increases as more protons are added (1 mark). Electrons are added to the same shell so shielding is similar; the increased nuclear charge pulls electrons closer (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why diamond is very hard but graphite is soft and slippery.', marks: 4, markScheme: 'Diamond has each carbon bonded to four others in a tetrahedral arrangement forming a rigid 3D network (1 mark). All bonds are strong covalent bonds requiring large energy to break (1 mark). Graphite has carbon atoms in layers with each bonded to three others (1 mark). Weak van der Waals forces between layers allow them to slide over each other (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Calculate the mass of 0.25 moles of calcium carbonate (CaCO3). (Mr = 100)', marks: 1, markScheme: 'Mass = n x Mr = 0.25 x 100 = 25 g (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'What is meant by the term electronegativity?', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Electronegativity is the ability of an atom to attract the bonding pair of electrons (1 mark) in a covalent bond towards itself (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why boron trifluoride (BF3) has a trigonal planar shape.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'BF3 has three bonding pairs and no lone pairs around the central boron atom (1 mark). The three bonding pairs repel equally and arrange themselves as far apart as possible, giving a trigonal planar shape with 120 degree bond angles (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'A sample of iron contains two isotopes: Fe-54 (5.8%) and Fe-56 (91.7%) and Fe-57 (2.2%) and Fe-58 (0.3%). Calculate the relative atomic mass of iron.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Ar = (54 x 5.8 + 56 x 91.7 + 57 x 2.2 + 58 x 0.3) / 100 (1 mark). Ar = (313.2 + 5135.2 + 125.4 + 17.4) / 100 = 55.91 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe what is meant by van der Waals forces (London dispersion forces).', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Temporary/instantaneous dipoles arise from random fluctuations in electron density (1 mark). These induce dipoles in neighbouring molecules (1 mark). The attraction between these temporary dipoles is the London dispersion force; it increases with the number of electrons/size of the electron cloud (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Write the electron configuration of the Fe^2+ ion.', marks: 1, markScheme: '[Ar] 3d6 (1 mark). Note: the 4s electrons are lost before the 3d electrons.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by a dative covalent (coordinate) bond. Give an example.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'A dative covalent bond is a shared pair of electrons where both electrons come from one atom (1 mark). The atom donating the pair must have a lone pair (1 mark). Example: the bond between NH3 and H+ in NH4+ (or CO donating to a metal in a complex) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Calculate the volume of 0.50 mol of nitrogen gas at room temperature and pressure (RTP).', marks: 2, markScheme: 'At RTP, 1 mol of gas occupies 24 dm^3 (1 mark). Volume = 0.50 x 24 = 12 dm^3 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'A solution of sodium hydroxide has a concentration of 0.20 mol dm^-3. Calculate the mass of NaOH in 250 cm^3 of this solution. (Mr NaOH = 40)', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Moles = 0.20 x 0.250 = 0.050 mol (1 mark). Mass = 0.050 x 40 = 2.0 g (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Predict the shape and bond angle of PCl3.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Trigonal pyramidal (1 mark). Bond angle approximately 107 degrees (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why hydrogen fluoride (HF) has a higher boiling point than hydrogen chloride (HCl).', marks: 3, markScheme: 'HF can form hydrogen bonds because fluorine is highly electronegative and small (1 mark). HCl can only form weaker dipole-dipole interactions (and London forces) as chlorine is less electronegative (1 mark). More energy is needed to overcome the stronger hydrogen bonds in HF (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'What is the percentage by mass of oxygen in Al2O3? (Ar: Al=27, O=16)', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Mr of Al2O3 = 2(27) + 3(16) = 102 (1 mark). % O = (48/102) x 100 = 47.1% (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe and explain the bonding in magnesium oxide.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Magnesium loses two electrons to form Mg^2+ and oxygen gains two electrons to form O^2- (1 mark). This is ionic bonding involving the transfer of electrons (1 mark). The strong electrostatic attraction between the Mg^2+ and O^2- ions forms the ionic bond (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State what is meant by an exothermic reaction in terms of enthalpy change.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'An exothermic reaction has a negative enthalpy change (delta H < 0), meaning energy is released to the surroundings (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why neon has a very low boiling point.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Neon exists as individual atoms with only weak London dispersion forces between them (1 mark). Very little energy is needed to overcome these weak forces (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Calculate the concentration in mol dm^-3 of a solution made by dissolving 5.85 g of NaCl in 500 cm^3 of water. (Mr NaCl = 58.5)', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Moles of NaCl = 5.85 / 58.5 = 0.10 mol (1 mark). Concentration = 0.10 / 0.500 = 0.20 mol dm^-3 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'What is the shape of a molecule of XeF4? Explain your answer.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Square planar (1 mark). Xe has 4 bonding pairs and 2 lone pairs (1 mark). The lone pairs occupy axial positions (above and below the plane) to minimise repulsion, leaving the 4 F atoms in a square plane (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Calculate the atom economy for the production of ethanol by fermentation: C6H12O6 -> 2C2H5OH + 2CO2. (Mr: C6H12O6 = 180, C2H5OH = 46, CO2 = 44)', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Atom economy = (Mr of desired product / Mr of all products) x 100 (1 mark). = (2 x 46) / (2 x 46 + 2 x 44) x 100 = 92/180 x 100 = 51.1% (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between a molecular formula and an empirical formula.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A molecular formula shows the actual number of atoms of each element in one molecule (1 mark). An empirical formula shows the simplest whole number ratio of atoms of each element in a compound (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State and explain the trend in first ionisation energy down Group 1.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'First ionisation energy decreases down Group 1 (1 mark). Atomic radius increases as more electron shells are added (1 mark). The outer electron is further from the nucleus and experiences more shielding, so less energy is needed to remove it (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Draw the shapes of s and p orbitals.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'S orbital: spherical shape drawn (1 mark). P orbital: dumbbell/figure-of-eight shape drawn with two lobes (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'A compound has the molecular formula C3H8O. Draw two possible structural isomers and name them.', marks: 4, markScheme: 'Propan-1-ol: CH3CH2CH2OH drawn correctly (1 mark) and named (1 mark). Propan-2-ol: CH3CH(OH)CH3 drawn correctly (1 mark) and named (1 mark). (Methoxyethane CH3OCH2CH3 also acceptable as one isomer.)' },
      { q: 'Explain why the second ionisation energy of sodium is much higher than the first.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'The first electron is removed from the 3s subshell (outer shell) (1 mark). The second electron must be removed from the 2p subshell, which is closer to the nucleus (1 mark). There is less shielding and stronger nuclear attraction on this inner electron, requiring much more energy (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Calculate the number of atoms in 6.4 g of sulfur (Ar of S = 32).', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Moles = 6.4 / 32 = 0.2 mol (1 mark). Number of atoms = 0.2 x 6.022 x 10^23 = 1.204 x 10^23 atoms (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why aluminium has a higher melting point than sodium.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Al has 3 delocalised electrons per atom compared to 1 for Na (1 mark). Al^3+ ion has a higher charge and smaller radius than Na+ (1 mark). This gives stronger metallic bonding (stronger electrostatic attraction between ions and delocalised electrons), requiring more energy to break (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Define the term Avogadro constant.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'The number of particles (atoms, molecules, or ions) in one mole of a substance, equal to 6.022 x 10^23 mol^-1 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Predict and explain whether BeCl2 or H2O has the higher boiling point.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'H2O has the higher boiling point (1 mark). H2O forms hydrogen bonds due to the high electronegativity of oxygen and lone pairs (1 mark). BeCl2 is a simple molecular compound with only weaker intermolecular forces (dipole-dipole and London forces) requiring less energy to overcome (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Write an ionic equation for the reaction between magnesium and hydrochloric acid.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Mg(s) + 2H+(aq) -> Mg^2+(aq) + H2(g) (1 mark for correct equation, 1 mark for correct state symbols).' },
      { q: 'A titration shows that 25.0 cm^3 of 0.10 mol dm^-3 NaOH neutralises 20.0 cm^3 of sulfuric acid. Calculate the concentration of the sulfuric acid.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Moles NaOH = 0.025 x 0.10 = 0.0025 mol (1 mark). 2NaOH + H2SO4 -> Na2SO4 + 2H2O, so moles H2SO4 = 0.0025/2 = 0.00125 mol (1 mark). Concentration = 0.00125 / 0.020 = 0.0625 mol dm^-3 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why ice is less dense than liquid water.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'In ice, water molecules form a regular open lattice structure held together by hydrogen bonds (1 mark). Each water molecule is hydrogen bonded to four others in a tetrahedral arrangement (1 mark). This open structure has more space between molecules than liquid water, making ice less dense (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'What are the conditions for hydrogen bonding to occur?', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A hydrogen atom must be bonded to a highly electronegative atom (N, O, or F) (1 mark). The electronegative atom must have a lone pair of electrons (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe the structure and bonding in sodium chloride.', marks: 4, markScheme: 'Giant ionic lattice structure (1 mark). Na+ and Cl- ions arranged in a regular 3D pattern (1 mark). Strong electrostatic attraction between oppositely charged ions (ionic bonds) (1 mark). Each Na+ is surrounded by 6 Cl- ions and vice versa (coordination number 6) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Calculate the volume of 2.0 g of hydrogen gas at RTP. (Ar of H = 1)', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Moles of H2 = 2.0 / 2.0 = 1.0 mol (1 mark). Volume = 1.0 x 24 = 24 dm^3 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain the trend in electronegativity across Period 2.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Electronegativity increases across Period 2 (from Li to F, excluding noble gases) (1 mark). Nuclear charge increases across the period as more protons are added (1 mark). Atomic radius decreases, so the bonding electrons are closer to the nucleus and more strongly attracted (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State the type of crystal structure in each of the following: NaCl, diamond, ice, copper.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'NaCl: giant ionic; diamond: giant covalent/macromolecular (1 mark). Ice: simple molecular; copper: giant metallic (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'A gas has a volume of 480 cm^3 at RTP. Calculate the number of moles.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'n = 480 / 24000 = 0.020 mol (1 mark).' }
    ]
  },
  'S2': {
    name: 'Energetics and Kinetics',
    questions: [
      { q: 'Define the term enthalpy of combustion.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The enthalpy change when one mole of a substance is completely burned (1 mark) in oxygen under standard conditions (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'In a calorimetry experiment, 50 cm^3 of 1.0 mol dm^-3 HCl was mixed with 50 cm^3 of 1.0 mol dm^-3 NaOH. The temperature rose by 6.5 degrees C. Calculate the enthalpy of neutralisation. (c = 4.18 J/g/K, density of solution = 1 g/cm^3)', marks: 3, markScheme: 'q = mc delta T = 100 x 4.18 x 6.5 = 2717 J = 2.717 kJ (1 mark). Moles of HCl (or NaOH) = 0.050 x 1.0 = 0.050 mol (1 mark). Delta H = -2.717 / 0.050 = -54.3 kJ/mol (negative sign for exothermic) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Draw an energy profile diagram for an exothermic reaction, labelling the activation energy and enthalpy change.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Correct shape with reactants higher than products (1 mark). Activation energy (Ea) labelled as the energy difference between reactants and the peak/transition state (1 mark). Delta H labelled as the energy difference between reactants and products, with a negative value (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why increasing the concentration of a reactant increases the rate of reaction.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Increasing concentration means more particles per unit volume (1 mark). Particles collide more frequently (1 mark). More collisions per unit time with energy >= Ea leads to a higher rate (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Using bond enthalpies, calculate the enthalpy change for: H2(g) + Cl2(g) -> 2HCl(g). Bond enthalpies: H-H = 436, Cl-Cl = 242, H-Cl = 431 kJ/mol.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Bonds broken: 1 x H-H + 1 x Cl-Cl = 436 + 242 = 678 kJ (1 mark). Bonds made: 2 x H-Cl = 2 x 431 = 862 kJ (1 mark). Delta H = 678 - 862 = -184 kJ/mol (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State two limitations of using mean bond enthalpies to calculate enthalpy changes.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Mean bond enthalpies are averages from many different compounds, so may not match the exact bond in the specific molecule (1 mark). They only apply to gaseous reactants and products; if substances are liquid or solid, additional energy changes (e.g., vaporisation) are not accounted for (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by a Maxwell-Boltzmann distribution.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A graph/distribution showing the range of energies (or speeds) that particles in a gas or solution have at a given temperature (1 mark). Most particles have moderate energies, with few having very low or very high energies (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Define the term entropy.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'Entropy (S) is a measure of the disorder or randomness of a system / the number of ways energy can be distributed among particles (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Predict and explain the sign of the entropy change for: CaCO3(s) -> CaO(s) + CO2(g).', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Delta S is positive (1 mark). A gas is produced from a solid, greatly increasing the disorder of the system since gaseous particles have much more freedom of movement (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Calculate delta G for a reaction where delta H = -120 kJ/mol and delta S = +200 J/K/mol at 298 K.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Delta G = delta H - T delta S = -120 - (298 x 0.200) (note: convert J to kJ) (1 mark). Delta G = -120 - 59.6 = -179.6 kJ/mol (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between the terms endothermic and exothermic.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Exothermic: energy is released to the surroundings, delta H is negative, temperature of surroundings increases (1 mark). Endothermic: energy is absorbed from the surroundings, delta H is positive, temperature of surroundings decreases (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State what is meant by the term lattice enthalpy.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The enthalpy change when one mole of an ionic compound is formed from its gaseous ions (1 mark) under standard conditions (lattice formation definition; or the energy to separate one mole of an ionic lattice into gaseous ions - lattice dissociation) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why the enthalpy of hydration of Mg^2+ is more exothermic than that of Na+.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Mg^2+ has a higher charge (+2 vs +1) (1 mark). Mg^2+ has a smaller ionic radius than Na+ (1 mark). Both factors result in a higher charge density, which attracts water molecules more strongly, releasing more energy during hydration (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State the rate equation for a reaction that is first order with respect to A and second order with respect to B.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'rate = k[A][B]^2 (1 mark). The overall order is 3 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Sketch a Maxwell-Boltzmann distribution and show the effect of adding a catalyst.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Correct M-B distribution curve drawn (asymmetric, starting at origin, with a peak) (1 mark). Original Ea marked on x-axis to the right of the peak (1 mark). New lower Ea marked to the left of original Ea, with shading showing the larger area (greater proportion of molecules with E >= Ea) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Define the term enthalpy of atomisation.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The enthalpy change when one mole of gaseous atoms is formed (1 mark) from the element in its standard state (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why the Arrhenius equation shows that rate constant increases exponentially with temperature.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'The Arrhenius equation is k = Ae^(-Ea/RT) (1 mark). As temperature T increases, the value of -Ea/RT becomes less negative (1 mark). Therefore e^(-Ea/RT) increases, and since k is proportional to this exponential term, the rate constant increases exponentially with temperature (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'A reaction has delta H = +50 kJ/mol and delta S = +150 J/K/mol. Calculate the minimum temperature for the reaction to be spontaneous.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'For spontaneity, delta G < 0, so delta H < T delta S. T > delta H / delta S (1 mark). T > 50000 / 150 = 333 K (must convert kJ to J or J to kJ consistently) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by the electron affinity of an element.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The first electron affinity is the enthalpy change when one mole of gaseous atoms gains one electron (1 mark) to form one mole of gaseous 1- ions (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'A catalyst increases the rate of reaction. Explain why a catalyst does NOT change the enthalpy change of the reaction.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A catalyst provides an alternative pathway with lower activation energy (1 mark). However, the initial reactants and final products are the same, so the overall energy difference (enthalpy change) is unchanged by Hess\'s law (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'What is meant by the term rate-determining step?', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The rate-determining step is the slowest step in a multi-step reaction mechanism (1 mark). It controls the overall rate of the reaction (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why increasing the surface area of a solid reactant increases the rate of reaction.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Increasing surface area exposes more particles of the solid to the other reactant (1 mark). This increases the frequency of collisions and therefore the rate of reaction (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Use Hess\'s law to calculate the enthalpy of formation of methane given: C(s) + O2(g) -> CO2(g), delta H = -393 kJ/mol; H2(g) + 1/2 O2(g) -> H2O(l), delta H = -286 kJ/mol; CH4(g) + 2O2(g) -> CO2(g) + 2H2O(l), delta H = -890 kJ/mol.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Delta Hf(CH4) = delta Hf(CO2) + 2 x delta Hf(H2O) - delta Hc(CH4) (1 mark). = (-393) + 2(-286) - (-890) (1 mark). = -393 - 572 + 890 = -75 kJ/mol (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State what happens to the value of the equilibrium constant when a catalyst is added.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'The equilibrium constant does not change when a catalyst is added; it remains the same (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why bond breaking is endothermic.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Energy must be supplied to overcome the electrostatic attraction between the bonding electrons and the nuclei (1 mark). This energy input makes the process endothermic (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'In a Born-Haber cycle, explain the purpose of the enthalpy of atomisation step.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The atomisation step converts the element from its standard state to individual gaseous atoms (1 mark). This is necessary because ionisation energies and electron affinities refer to gaseous species (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State the units of the rate constant k for a first-order reaction.', marks: 1, markScheme: 's^-1 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why the enthalpy change calculated using mean bond enthalpies often differs from the experimentally determined value.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Mean bond enthalpies are averaged over many different molecules/environments (1 mark). The actual bond enthalpy in a specific molecule may differ from the mean due to the influence of neighbouring atoms/groups (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'A reaction has an activation energy of 75 kJ/mol. Explain how a catalyst with Ea = 50 kJ/mol affects the rate.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The catalyst lowers the activation energy from 75 to 50 kJ/mol (1 mark). A greater proportion of particles now have energy >= 50 kJ/mol, so more successful collisions occur per unit time and the rate increases significantly (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why dissolving ammonium nitrate in water feels cold to the touch.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Dissolving ammonium nitrate is endothermic (positive delta H of solution) (1 mark). Energy is absorbed from the surroundings (the water and your hand), causing the temperature to decrease (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Define the term enthalpy of solution.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The enthalpy change when one mole of a solute dissolves (1 mark) in sufficient solvent to form an infinitely dilute solution (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'The rate of a reaction doubles when the temperature increases from 300 K to 310 K. Explain this observation using collision theory.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'The increase in temperature gives particles more kinetic energy (1 mark). The Maxwell-Boltzmann distribution shifts right, and a significantly greater proportion of particles have energy >= Ea (1 mark). The small temperature increase causes a large change in the proportion of particles exceeding Ea, approximately doubling the number of successful collisions per second (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain the relationship between lattice enthalpy and the charge and size of ions.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Lattice enthalpy becomes more exothermic with increasing ionic charge (1 mark). Lattice enthalpy becomes more exothermic with decreasing ionic radius (1 mark). Both factors increase the charge density and electrostatic attraction between ions in the lattice (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'What is meant by a feasible reaction? Is a feasible reaction guaranteed to occur?', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A feasible (thermodynamically spontaneous) reaction has delta G < 0 (1 mark). However, it may not occur at an observable rate if the activation energy is too high (kinetic barrier), so feasibility does not guarantee the reaction will happen (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State Le Chatelier\'s principle and use it to predict the effect of increasing pressure on N2(g) + 3H2(g) <=> 2NH3(g).', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Le Chatelier\'s principle: a system at equilibrium opposes any change imposed upon it (1 mark). Increasing pressure favours the side with fewer moles of gas (1 mark). The equilibrium shifts to the right (towards NH3) as 2 moles is fewer than 4 moles of gas (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'What is the difference between the enthalpy of hydration and the enthalpy of solution?', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Enthalpy of hydration is the enthalpy change when one mole of gaseous ions is dissolved in water/surrounded by water molecules (1 mark). Enthalpy of solution is the overall enthalpy change when one mole of an ionic solid dissolves in water, and equals the sum of lattice dissociation enthalpy and enthalpies of hydration (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Sketch a graph of 1/time against concentration for a reaction. What does the gradient represent?', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A straight line through the origin for a first-order or proportional relationship (1 mark). 1/time is proportional to rate, so the gradient is related to the rate constant (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Calculate the entropy change for a reaction where delta H = -200 kJ/mol and delta G = -150 kJ/mol at 298 K.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Delta G = delta H - T delta S, so delta S = (delta H - delta G) / T (1 mark). delta S = (-200 - (-150)) / 298 = -50/298 = -0.168 kJ/K/mol = -168 J/K/mol (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Why is the second electron affinity of oxygen positive (endothermic)?', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The second electron is being added to an already negatively charged O^- ion (1 mark). There is electrostatic repulsion between the incoming electron and the existing negative charge, so energy must be supplied to force the electron onto the ion (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why increasing temperature changes the value of the equilibrium constant Kc.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Temperature changes affect the rates of forward and reverse reactions differently (1 mark). For an exothermic reaction, increasing temperature favours the endothermic (reverse) direction, shifting equilibrium left and decreasing Kc (1 mark). For an endothermic reaction, increasing temperature favours the forward direction, increasing Kc (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'A reaction is second order overall with rate = k[X]^2. Sketch a graph of rate against [X].', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Graph shows rate on y-axis and [X] on x-axis (1 mark). A curve (parabola) starting from the origin, curving upward (rate increases as square of concentration) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why the standard enthalpy of formation of an element in its standard state is zero.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The enthalpy of formation is defined as forming a compound from its elements in standard states (1 mark). Since the element is already in its standard state, no change occurs, so delta H = 0 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'In a gas phase reaction, why does increasing pressure increase the rate?', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Increasing pressure reduces the volume, so particles are closer together / higher concentration (1 mark). This increases the frequency of collisions, leading to more successful collisions per unit time and a higher rate (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'What is the difference between homogeneous and heterogeneous catalysis?', marks: 2, markScheme: 'In homogeneous catalysis, the catalyst is in the same phase as the reactants (e.g., both in solution) (1 mark). In heterogeneous catalysis, the catalyst is in a different phase from the reactants (e.g., a solid catalyst with gaseous reactants) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Define the term mean bond enthalpy.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The average energy required to break one mole of a particular type of bond (1 mark) in the gaseous state, averaged over a range of different compounds containing that bond (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Why are experimental lattice enthalpies for compounds with significant covalent character (e.g., AgI) different from theoretical values?', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Theoretical lattice enthalpies assume the compound is purely ionic with spherical ion charge distributions (1 mark). In compounds like AgI, the large, polarisable iodide ion is distorted by the small, highly charged Ag+ ion (1 mark). This gives the bonding partial covalent character, making the experimental lattice enthalpy more exothermic than the theoretical (purely ionic) value (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State and explain the effect of temperature on the rate of an enzyme-catalysed reaction.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Increasing temperature initially increases the rate as particles have more kinetic energy and collisions are more frequent (1 mark). Above the optimum temperature, the enzyme denatures as hydrogen bonds and other interactions maintaining its 3D shape break (1 mark). The active site changes shape and can no longer bind the substrate, so the rate decreases dramatically (1 mark).' }
    ]
  },
  'S3': {
    name: 'Equilibrium and Acid-Base Chemistry',
    questions: [
      { q: 'State what is meant by a dynamic equilibrium.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A dynamic equilibrium is when the rate of the forward reaction equals the rate of the reverse reaction (1 mark) and the concentrations of reactants and products remain constant (but not necessarily equal) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Write the expression for Kc for the reaction: 2SO2(g) + O2(g) <=> 2SO3(g).', marks: 1, markScheme: 'Kc = [SO3]^2 / ([SO2]^2 [O2]) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Define the term weak acid and give an example.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A weak acid is one that only partially dissociates/ionises in aqueous solution (1 mark). Example: ethanoic acid (CH3COOH) or carbonic acid (H2CO3) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Calculate the pH of a 0.001 mol dm^-3 solution of HNO3.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'HNO3 is a strong acid: [H+] = 0.001 mol dm^-3. pH = -log(0.001) = 3 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain what happens to the position of equilibrium and the value of Kc when the concentration of a product is increased.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'The equilibrium shifts to the left (towards reactants) to oppose the change (1 mark). This reduces the concentration of the added product and increases reactant concentrations (1 mark). The value of Kc remains unchanged because Kc only changes with temperature (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Define the term conjugate acid-base pair.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A conjugate acid-base pair consists of two species that differ by one proton (H+) (1 mark). The conjugate base is formed when the acid donates a proton; the conjugate acid is formed when the base accepts a proton (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Calculate [OH^-] and pH for a 0.050 mol dm^-3 solution of NaOH at 25 degrees C. (Kw = 1.0 x 10^-14)', marks: 3, markScheme: '[OH^-] = 0.050 mol dm^-3 (NaOH is a strong base, fully dissociates) (1 mark). [H+] = Kw / [OH^-] = 1.0 x 10^-14 / 0.050 = 2.0 x 10^-13 mol dm^-3 (1 mark). pH = -log(2.0 x 10^-13) = 12.70 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why increasing temperature increases the value of Kw.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'The dissociation of water (H2O <=> H+ + OH^-) is endothermic (1 mark). Increasing temperature favours the endothermic forward reaction (Le Chatelier) (1 mark). More H+ and OH^- ions are produced, so the product [H+][OH^-] = Kw increases (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain what a buffer solution is and give an example of an acidic buffer.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'A buffer solution resists changes in pH when small amounts of acid or base are added (1 mark). An acidic buffer is made from a weak acid and its conjugate base/salt (1 mark). Example: ethanoic acid and sodium ethanoate (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'For the equilibrium PCl5(g) <=> PCl3(g) + Cl2(g), predict the effect of decreasing the total pressure on the position of equilibrium.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Equilibrium shifts to the right (towards more moles of gas) (1 mark). The right side has 2 moles of gas vs 1 on the left, so shifting right increases the total moles of gas to oppose the pressure decrease (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Calculate the pH of a 0.20 mol dm^-3 solution of CH3COOH. Ka = 1.74 x 10^-5 mol dm^-3.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Ka = [H+]^2 / [CH3COOH] (assuming small dissociation) (1 mark). [H+] = sqrt(Ka x c) = sqrt(1.74 x 10^-5 x 0.20) = sqrt(3.48 x 10^-6) = 1.87 x 10^-3 (1 mark). pH = -log(1.87 x 10^-3) = 2.73 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'What is meant by the term ionic product of water (Kw)?', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Kw is the equilibrium constant for the dissociation of water: H2O <=> H+ + OH^- (1 mark). Kw = [H+][OH^-] = 1.0 x 10^-14 mol^2 dm^-6 at 25 degrees C (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why the pH at the equivalence point of a strong acid-weak base titration is less than 7.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'At the equivalence point, all the weak base has reacted with the strong acid (1 mark). The salt formed contains the conjugate acid of the weak base (1 mark). This conjugate acid hydrolyses/dissociates in water to release H+ ions, making the solution acidic (pH < 7) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Write the Henderson-Hasselbalch equation and state what each term represents.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'pH = pKa + log([A^-]/[HA]) (1 mark). pKa = -log(Ka), [A^-] is the concentration of conjugate base, [HA] is the concentration of weak acid (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Calculate the pH of a buffer solution containing 0.30 mol dm^-3 ethanoic acid and 0.50 mol dm^-3 sodium ethanoate. Ka = 1.74 x 10^-5.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'pH = pKa + log([A^-]/[HA]) (1 mark). pKa = -log(1.74 x 10^-5) = 4.76 (1 mark). pH = 4.76 + log(0.50/0.30) = 4.76 + 0.22 = 4.98 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Define the term partial pressure and state how it is calculated.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Partial pressure is the pressure that a gas in a mixture would exert if it alone occupied the entire volume (1 mark). Partial pressure = mole fraction x total pressure (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why a strong acid-strong base titration uses any indicator that changes near pH 7.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The pH changes very sharply (steeply) at the equivalence point, covering a wide pH range (1 mark). Any indicator that changes colour within this steep region will give an accurate end point (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between the end point and the equivalence point in a titration.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The equivalence point is the exact point where the moles of acid equal the moles of base stoichiometrically (1 mark). The end point is the point at which the indicator changes colour, which should be as close as possible to the equivalence point (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'A 0.10 mol dm^-3 solution of ammonia (Kb = 1.8 x 10^-5) is prepared. Calculate its pH.', marks: 4, markScheme: 'Kb = [NH4+][OH^-] / [NH3] (1 mark). [OH^-] = sqrt(Kb x c) = sqrt(1.8 x 10^-5 x 0.10) = sqrt(1.8 x 10^-6) = 1.34 x 10^-3 mol dm^-3 (1 mark). pOH = -log(1.34 x 10^-3) = 2.87 (1 mark). pH = 14 - 2.87 = 11.13 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why adding sodium chloride to a system at equilibrium has no effect on the position of equilibrium.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Sodium chloride is not involved in the equilibrium reaction (it is a spectator) (1 mark). Since it does not appear in the equilibrium expression, adding it does not change the concentrations of any species in the expression, so the position is unaffected (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'What is a titration curve? Sketch the titration curve for a strong acid being titrated with a strong base.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'A titration curve is a graph of pH against volume of titrant added (1 mark). The curve starts at a low pH (around 1) and remains low until near the equivalence point (1 mark). There is a very steep rise at the equivalence point (pH jumps from about 3 to 11) and then levels off at a high pH (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why phenolphthalein is a suitable indicator for a weak acid-strong base titration.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The equivalence point for a weak acid-strong base titration is above pH 7 (around pH 8-10) (1 mark). Phenolphthalein changes colour between pH 8.2 and 10.0, which falls within the steep part of the titration curve near the equivalence point (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State the effect of increasing temperature on an exothermic equilibrium. Explain your answer.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'The equilibrium shifts to the left (endothermic direction) (1 mark). This is because the system opposes the increase in temperature by absorbing energy via the reverse reaction (1 mark). The value of Kc decreases as the position shifts towards reactants (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by the common ion effect.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The common ion effect is the suppression of the dissociation of a weak electrolyte (1 mark) when a strong electrolyte containing a common ion is added to the solution, shifting the equilibrium to reduce the concentration of that ion (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Calculate the solubility of lead(II) chloride given Ksp = 1.7 x 10^-5 mol^3 dm^-9.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'PbCl2 <=> Pb^2+ + 2Cl^-. If solubility = s, then [Pb^2+] = s and [Cl^-] = 2s (1 mark). Ksp = s(2s)^2 = 4s^3 (1 mark). s = (1.7 x 10^-5 / 4)^(1/3) = (4.25 x 10^-6)^(1/3) = 1.62 x 10^-2 mol dm^-3 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain what happens when a buffer solution absorbs a small amount of added alkali.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'The added OH^- ions react with the weak acid component of the buffer: HA + OH^- -> A^- + H2O (1 mark). This removes the added OH^- ions, preventing a large increase in pH (1 mark). The ratio [A^-]/[HA] changes only slightly because the buffer has large reserves of both components (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'For the equilibrium 2NO(g) + O2(g) <=> 2NO2(g), Kc = 4.0 at 500 K. If [NO] = 0.20, [O2] = 0.10, and [NO2] = 0.40, is the system at equilibrium?', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Calculate the reaction quotient Q = [NO2]^2 / ([NO]^2 [O2]) (1 mark). Q = (0.40)^2 / ((0.20)^2 x 0.10) = 0.16 / 0.004 = 40 (1 mark). Q > Kc, so the system is not at equilibrium; it will shift to the left to decrease Q towards Kc (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'What is the significance of pKa?', marks: 2, markScheme: 'pKa = -log(Ka) and is a measure of the strength of an acid (1 mark). A lower pKa indicates a stronger acid (larger Ka, greater degree of dissociation) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why the pH of pure water increases above 7 when the temperature is lowered below 25 degrees C.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'The dissociation of water is endothermic (1 mark). At lower temperatures, the equilibrium H2O <=> H+ + OH^- shifts to the left, producing fewer H+ and OH^- ions (1 mark). Kw decreases, so [H+] decreases and pH = -log[H+] increases above 7 (though the water is still neutral as [H+] = [OH^-]) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State two conditions required for a system to reach dynamic equilibrium.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The system must be closed (no substances entering or leaving) (1 mark). The reaction must be reversible (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'A solution of HCl has pH = 2. Calculate the volume of 0.050 mol dm^-3 NaOH needed to neutralise 25.0 cm^3 of this acid.', marks: 3, markScheme: '[H+] = 10^-2 = 0.01 mol dm^-3 (1 mark). Moles HCl = 0.01 x 0.025 = 2.5 x 10^-4 mol. Since HCl + NaOH is 1:1, moles NaOH = 2.5 x 10^-4 (1 mark). Volume = 2.5 x 10^-4 / 0.050 = 0.005 dm^3 = 5.0 cm^3 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Define the acid dissociation constant Ka.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'For a weak acid HA dissociating as HA <=> H+ + A^-, Ka = [H+][A^-] / [HA] (1 mark). Ka is the equilibrium constant for the dissociation of a weak acid in water; a larger Ka indicates a stronger acid (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why a mixture of a strong acid and its conjugate base does NOT make an effective buffer.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A strong acid fully dissociates, so there is no equilibrium between the acid and conjugate base (1 mark). Without this equilibrium, the solution cannot resist pH changes because there is no reservoir of undissociated acid to react with added base (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'The Ksp of BaSO4 is 1.1 x 10^-10. Will a precipitate form if 50 cm^3 of 0.001 mol dm^-3 BaCl2 is mixed with 50 cm^3 of 0.001 mol dm^-3 Na2SO4?', marks: 3, markScheme: 'After mixing, volume = 100 cm^3, so concentrations halve: [Ba^2+] = 0.0005, [SO4^2-] = 0.0005 mol dm^-3 (1 mark). Q = [Ba^2+][SO4^2-] = 0.0005 x 0.0005 = 2.5 x 10^-7 (1 mark). Q > Ksp (2.5 x 10^-7 > 1.1 x 10^-10), so a precipitate will form (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why methyl orange is NOT suitable for a weak acid-strong base titration.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Methyl orange changes colour between pH 3.1 and 4.4 (1 mark). The equivalence point of a weak acid-strong base titration is above pH 7, which is well outside the range of methyl orange, so the end point would not coincide with the equivalence point (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Write the equilibrium expression for Kp for: CaCO3(s) <=> CaO(s) + CO2(g).', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Kp = p(CO2) (1 mark). Pure solids (CaCO3 and CaO) are not included in the equilibrium expression (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why diluting a buffer solution only slightly changes its pH.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'When water is added, the concentrations of both the weak acid and conjugate base decrease by the same factor (1 mark). The ratio [A^-]/[HA] remains approximately the same, so pH = pKa + log([A^-]/[HA]) hardly changes (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'A weak acid HA has Ka = 4.0 x 10^-4. Calculate the concentration of HA needed to give pH = 2.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'pH = 2, so [H+] = 0.01 mol dm^-3 (1 mark). Ka = [H+]^2 / [HA], so [HA] = [H+]^2 / Ka = (0.01)^2 / 4.0 x 10^-4 (1 mark). [HA] = 1.0 x 10^-4 / 4.0 x 10^-4 = 0.25 mol dm^-3 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State and explain the effect of adding an inert gas at constant volume to a gaseous equilibrium.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Adding an inert gas at constant volume does not change the partial pressures of the reacting gases (1 mark). Therefore the equilibrium position and Kp are unaffected (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why water is described as amphoteric (amphiprotic).', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Water can act as an acid by donating a proton: H2O -> H+ + OH^- (1 mark). Water can also act as a base by accepting a proton: H2O + H+ -> H3O+ (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'For the equilibrium CO(g) + 2H2(g) <=> CH3OH(g), delta H = -90 kJ/mol. State and explain the conditions that favour a high yield of methanol.', marks: 4, markScheme: 'Low temperature favours the exothermic forward reaction, shifting equilibrium right (1 mark). However, low temperature reduces rate, so a compromise temperature is used (1 mark). High pressure shifts equilibrium to the right as there are fewer moles of gas on the product side (3 -> 1) (1 mark). A catalyst increases the rate of reaching equilibrium but does not change the yield (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between Kc and Kp.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Kc is the equilibrium constant expressed in terms of concentrations (mol dm^-3) of reactants and products (1 mark). Kp is the equilibrium constant expressed in terms of partial pressures of gaseous reactants and products, and is used for gas-phase equilibria (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Calculate pOH and then pH for a solution where [OH^-] = 0.0020 mol dm^-3 at 25 degrees C.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'pOH = -log(0.0020) = 2.70 (1 mark). pH = 14 - 2.70 = 11.30 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State why only temperature changes the value of an equilibrium constant.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The equilibrium constant is defined at a specific temperature (1 mark). Changes in concentration or pressure shift the position of equilibrium but the ratio defined by the equilibrium expression returns to the same value; only temperature changes the relative rates of forward and reverse reactions unequally, altering the constant (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'A student mixes equal volumes of 0.10 mol dm^-3 CH3COOH and 0.10 mol dm^-3 CH3COONa. Calculate the pH. Ka = 1.74 x 10^-5.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Since equal volumes are mixed, [CH3COOH] = [CH3COO^-] (both halved equally). pH = pKa + log(1) = pKa + 0 (1 mark). pH = -log(1.74 x 10^-5) = 4.76 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain the term mole fraction and how it relates to partial pressure.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Mole fraction is the ratio of moles of one component to the total moles in the mixture (1 mark). Partial pressure = mole fraction x total pressure (Dalton\'s law) (1 mark).' }
    ]
  },
  'S4': {
    name: 'Organic Chemistry',
    questions: [
      { q: 'Define the term homologous series.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A series of organic compounds with the same general formula (1 mark) and similar chemical properties, with each successive member differing by CH2 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Name and give the molecular formula of the first four members of the alkane series.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Methane CH4, Ethane C2H6, Propane C3H8, Butane C4H10 (1 mark for names, 1 mark for all formulae correct).' },
      { q: 'Explain why alkenes are described as unsaturated hydrocarbons.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Alkenes contain only carbon and hydrogen (hydrocarbons) (1 mark). They contain a C=C double bond, meaning they have fewer than the maximum number of hydrogen atoms (unsaturated), and can undergo addition reactions (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'What type of reaction occurs when ethene reacts with steam? State the conditions.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Electrophilic addition / hydration (1 mark). Conditions: high temperature (about 300 degrees C), high pressure (about 60-70 atm) (1 mark), and H3PO4 (phosphoric acid) catalyst (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why the C-I bond in iodoalkanes is weaker than the C-Cl bond in chloroalkanes.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Iodine has a much larger atomic radius than chlorine (1 mark). The C-I bond is longer, so the electron density is spread over a greater distance, making the bond weaker/lower bond enthalpy (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe the initiation step in the free radical substitution of methane with chlorine.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'UV light causes homolytic fission of the Cl-Cl bond (1 mark). This produces two chlorine free radicals: Cl2 -> 2Cl* (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State the reagent and conditions needed to convert ethanol to ethanoic acid.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Acidified potassium dichromate (K2Cr2O7 / H2SO4) (1 mark). Heat under reflux (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by a nucleophile.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A nucleophile is an electron-pair donor (1 mark) that is attracted to and attacks an electron-deficient (delta positive) carbon atom (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Draw and name two structural isomers of C3H7Br.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1-bromopropane: CH3CH2CH2Br (1 mark). 2-bromopropane: CH3CHBrCH3 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe and explain the trend in boiling points of the first four straight-chain alcohols.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Boiling points increase from methanol to butanol (1 mark). As the chain length increases, the number of electrons and surface area increase (1 mark). This increases the strength of London dispersion forces between molecules, requiring more energy to overcome (1 mark). All also have hydrogen bonding due to the OH group.' },
      { q: 'What is the role of concentrated sulfuric acid in the dehydration of an alcohol?', marks: 1, markScheme: 'Concentrated sulfuric acid acts as a catalyst / dehydrating agent, facilitating the removal of water from the alcohol to form an alkene (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State what is meant by E/Z isomerism and give the two conditions needed for it to occur.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'E/Z isomerism is a type of stereoisomerism where molecules have the same structural formula but different spatial arrangements around a C=C double bond (1 mark). A C=C double bond must be present (which prevents free rotation) (1 mark). Each carbon of the double bond must have two different groups attached (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'A primary alcohol can be oxidised to an aldehyde. What reagent and conditions are used, and how is the aldehyde collected?', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Acidified potassium dichromate (K2Cr2O7 with H2SO4) (1 mark). The mixture is heated gently (1 mark). The aldehyde is collected by distillation as it forms, to prevent further oxidation to carboxylic acid (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why secondary alcohols produce ketones on oxidation but cannot be further oxidised to carboxylic acids.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Secondary alcohols have two carbon groups attached to the C-OH carbon, oxidation removes the H from C-OH and from C-H to form a C=O (ketone) (1 mark). Further oxidation would require breaking a C-C bond, which does not occur with mild oxidising agents like acidified dichromate (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Write the equation for the complete combustion of propan-1-ol.', marks: 2, markScheme: '2C3H7OH + 9O2 -> 6CO2 + 8H2O (1 mark for correct products, 1 mark for balanced equation).' },
      { q: 'Describe the mechanism of the reaction between chlorine and methane in UV light (free radical substitution). Include initiation, propagation, and termination.', marks: 6, markScheme: 'Initiation: Cl2 -> 2Cl* (homolytic fission by UV) (1 mark). Propagation step 1: CH4 + Cl* -> CH3* + HCl (1 mark). Propagation step 2: CH3* + Cl2 -> CH3Cl + Cl* (1 mark). The chlorine radical is regenerated in propagation (chain reaction) (1 mark). Termination: two radicals combine, e.g., CH3* + Cl* -> CH3Cl, or CH3* + CH3* -> C2H6, or Cl* + Cl* -> Cl2 (1 mark for any two correct termination steps, 1 mark overall for correct radical notation with dots throughout).' },
      { q: 'State what is meant by a chiral centre. How many chiral centres does 2-bromobutane have?', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A chiral centre is a carbon atom bonded to four different groups/atoms (1 mark). 2-bromobutane (CH3CHBrCH2CH3) has one chiral centre at C-2 (bonded to H, Br, CH3, C2H5) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe the difference between SN1 and SN2 mechanisms in terms of the number of steps.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'SN1 is a two-step mechanism: first the C-X bond breaks (heterolytic fission) to form a carbocation, then the nucleophile attacks (1 mark). SN2 is a one-step (concerted) mechanism where the nucleophile attacks at the same time as the leaving group departs (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why ethanol produced by fermentation is considered carbon-neutral, while ethanol produced from ethene is not.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Fermentation uses sugars from plants that absorbed CO2 during photosynthesis (1 mark). The CO2 released during fermentation and combustion of the ethanol equals the CO2 absorbed by the plant, making it carbon-neutral overall (1 mark). Ethanol from ethene uses ethene derived from cracking of crude oil (a fossil fuel), and the CO2 released adds new carbon to the atmosphere (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'What is Markovnikov\'s rule?', marks: 2, markScheme: 'When HX adds to an unsymmetrical alkene, the hydrogen atom adds to the carbon of the double bond that already has more hydrogen atoms (1 mark). This produces the more substituted (more stable) carbocation intermediate as the major product (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why the C=C bond in alkenes is electron-rich and attracts electrophiles.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The C=C double bond contains a pi bond with electron density above and below the bond axis (1 mark). This region of high electron density attracts electrophiles (electron-pair acceptors), which are positively charged or electron-deficient species (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State the products when butan-2-ol is heated with concentrated H2SO4.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Elimination/dehydration occurs to form butene(s) and water (1 mark). Both but-1-ene and but-2-ene (E and Z forms) can be produced (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain the term optical isomerism and state how enantiomers differ.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Optical isomerism occurs when a molecule has a chiral centre (carbon bonded to 4 different groups) (1 mark). Enantiomers are non-superimposable mirror images of each other (1 mark). They have identical physical and chemical properties except they rotate the plane of polarised light in opposite directions (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe the test to determine whether an organic compound is a primary, secondary, or tertiary alcohol.', marks: 4, markScheme: 'Add acidified potassium dichromate and warm (1 mark). Primary alcohol: solution turns from orange to green (oxidised to aldehyde/carboxylic acid) (1 mark). Secondary alcohol: solution turns from orange to green (oxidised to ketone) (1 mark). Tertiary alcohol: no colour change (cannot be oxidised by this reagent) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Write the mechanism for the electrophilic addition of Br2 to ethene.', marks: 4, markScheme: 'As Br2 approaches the electron-rich C=C, it becomes polarised (induced dipole) (1 mark). Curly arrow from C=C to nearer Br; curly arrow from Br-Br bond to far Br, showing heterolytic fission producing Br^- (1 mark). A carbocation intermediate forms (with Br attached and a positive charge on carbon) (1 mark). Curly arrow from lone pair on Br^- to the positive carbon, forming 1,2-dibromoethane (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Give the reagent and conditions to convert a halogenoalkane to an alcohol by nucleophilic substitution.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Aqueous sodium hydroxide (NaOH(aq)) / dilute NaOH (1 mark). Heat under reflux (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why halogenoalkanes undergo nucleophilic substitution.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'The carbon-halogen bond is polar because the halogen is more electronegative than carbon (1 mark). The carbon atom is delta positive (electron deficient) (1 mark). This attracts nucleophiles, which donate an electron pair to the carbon, displacing the halide ion as a leaving group (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe the conditions for the elimination reaction of 2-bromopropane to form propene.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Heat with ethanolic potassium hydroxide (KOH dissolved in ethanol) (1 mark). The ethanol acts as a solvent and the OH^- acts as a base, removing a hydrogen and the bromide (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'What is the difference between elimination and substitution reactions of halogenoalkanes?', marks: 2, markScheme: 'In substitution, the halogen is replaced by another group (e.g., OH^-) and the carbon skeleton is maintained (1 mark). In elimination, a hydrogen and the halogen are removed from adjacent carbons, forming a double bond (alkene) and a small molecule (HX) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why addition polymers are generally non-biodegradable.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Addition polymers have a backbone of C-C single bonds which are strong and unreactive (1 mark). Microorganisms lack the enzymes needed to break down these C-C bonds, so the polymer persists in the environment (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Draw the repeating unit of poly(propene).', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The repeating unit shows -CH2-CH(CH3)- with continuation bonds at each end (1 mark for correct structure, 1 mark for correct representation with brackets and n).' },
      { q: 'Classify each alcohol as primary, secondary, or tertiary: (a) butan-1-ol, (b) butan-2-ol, (c) 2-methylpropan-2-ol.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(a) Butan-1-ol: primary (the OH is on a carbon bonded to one other carbon) (1 mark). (b) Butan-2-ol: secondary (OH is on a carbon bonded to two other carbons) (1 mark). (c) 2-methylpropan-2-ol: tertiary (OH is on a carbon bonded to three other carbons) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why propan-1-ol has a higher boiling point than propane despite having a similar molecular mass.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Propan-1-ol contains an OH group that can form hydrogen bonds with other propan-1-ol molecules (1 mark). Propane can only form weaker London dispersion forces (1 mark). More energy is required to overcome the stronger hydrogen bonds, giving propan-1-ol a higher boiling point (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Write an equation for the esterification reaction between ethanol and propanoic acid.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'CH3CH2OH + CH3CH2COOH -> CH3CH2COOCH2CH3 + H2O (1 mark for correct products, 1 mark for balanced equation). Product is ethyl propanoate.' },
      { q: 'State two conditions needed for esterification.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'Heat under reflux with a concentrated sulfuric acid catalyst (1 mark for both conditions).' },
      { q: 'What is cracking and why is it important?', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Cracking is the breaking down of long-chain hydrocarbons into shorter, more useful ones (1 mark). It produces alkenes for making polymers and other chemicals (1 mark). It helps match the supply of petroleum fractions to demand, as short-chain fractions are more useful as fuels (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Draw the displayed formula of but-2-ene and explain why it shows E/Z isomerism.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Correct displayed formula showing CH3-CH=CH-CH3 with all bonds drawn out (1 mark). The C=C double bond prevents free rotation (1 mark). Each carbon of the double bond has two different groups (H and CH3), so E and Z forms exist with groups on same side (Z) or opposite sides (E) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe how infrared spectroscopy can distinguish between ethanol and ethanoic acid.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Both show O-H absorption, but the O-H in ethanoic acid appears as a very broad absorption at 2500-3300 cm^-1 (1 mark). Ethanoic acid shows a strong C=O absorption at around 1710 cm^-1 which ethanol does not have (1 mark). Ethanol shows a sharper O-H absorption around 3230-3550 cm^-1 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Define the term electrophile and give two examples.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'An electrophile is an electron-pair acceptor that is attracted to regions of high electron density (1 mark). Examples: H+, NO2+, Br2 (when polarised), H3O+, carbocations (any two for 1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between catalytic cracking and thermal cracking.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Thermal cracking uses high temperatures (up to 1000 degrees C) and high pressure, and tends to produce alkenes (1 mark). Catalytic cracking uses a zeolite catalyst at lower temperatures and produces more branched alkanes and aromatic compounds useful for petrol (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'A compound C2H4Br2 can be formed by the reaction of ethene with bromine. Describe the observation and name the mechanism.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Bromine water is decolourised from orange/brown to colourless (1 mark). The mechanism is electrophilic addition (1 mark). Product is 1,2-dibromoethane.' },
      { q: 'Explain why chloroethane reacts faster with NaOH(aq) than chloromethane.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The ethyl group in chloroethane has a slight positive inductive effect that helps stabilise the transition state or carbocation intermediate (1 mark). However the main factor is that primary halogenoalkanes react similarly by SN2; the question may refer to the fact that longer chains provide slightly more stable intermediates. Actually, chloromethane can also react by SN2 readily. The key difference is that the increased chain length slightly increases the electron density on carbon or that the C-Cl bond is slightly more polarised (1 mark). Accept: both react by SN2 at similar rates; the question tests understanding of substitution mechanisms.' },
      { q: 'What is a racemic mixture and why is it optically inactive?', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A racemic mixture contains equal amounts of both enantiomers of a chiral compound (1 mark). It is optically inactive because the rotation of plane-polarised light by one enantiomer is exactly cancelled by the equal and opposite rotation of the other (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Give the reagents and conditions to convert propan-1-ol to 1-bromopropane.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'NaBr and concentrated H2SO4 (or use HBr directly / or 50% H2SO4 with KBr) (1 mark). Heat under reflux (1 mark). The reaction is nucleophilic substitution with Br^- as the nucleophile.' },
      { q: 'Explain why the boiling points of straight-chain alkanes increase with increasing chain length.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Longer chains have more electrons and a greater surface area of contact between molecules (1 mark). This increases the strength of London dispersion forces between molecules, requiring more energy to overcome (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe how you could experimentally determine whether a liquid is an alkene or an alkane.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Add bromine water to separate samples (1 mark). If the bromine water is decolourised (orange to colourless), the compound is an alkene (1 mark). If no colour change occurs, the compound is an alkane (1 mark).' }
    ]
  },
  'S5': {
    name: 'Redox, Electrochemistry and Transition Metals',
    questions: [
      { q: 'Define oxidation in terms of oxidation state.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'Oxidation is an increase in oxidation state (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Assign oxidation states to all atoms in H2SO4.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'H = +1, O = -2 (1 mark). S: 2(+1) + S + 4(-2) = 0, so S = +6 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'What is a half-equation? Write a half-equation for the reduction of MnO4^- to Mn^2+ in acid solution.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'A half-equation shows either the oxidation or reduction process separately (1 mark). MnO4^- + 8H+ + 5e^- -> Mn^2+ + 4H2O (1 mark for correct species, 1 mark for balanced charge and atoms).' },
      { q: 'State two reasons why transition metals are used as catalysts in industry.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'They have variable oxidation states allowing them to cycle between states during catalysis (1 mark). They can provide a surface for adsorption of reactants / form intermediates with reactants (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'What is the oxidation state of Fe in [Fe(H2O)6]^3+?', marks: 1, markScheme: 'H2O is a neutral ligand so contributes 0 to the charge. Fe must be +3 to give overall 3+ charge (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe the colour change when acidified potassium dichromate is reduced.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'Orange (Cr2O7^2-) changes to green (Cr^3+) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Write the overall cell equation for the reaction between zinc metal and copper(II) sulfate solution.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Zn(s) + CuSO4(aq) -> ZnSO4(aq) + Cu(s) or Zn(s) + Cu^2+(aq) -> Zn^2+(aq) + Cu(s) (1 mark for correct equation, 1 mark for state symbols).' },
      { q: 'What is meant by the term coordination number?', marks: 1, markScheme: 'The coordination number is the total number of coordinate bonds from ligands to the central metal ion (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why Zn^2+ compounds are white/colourless.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Zn^2+ has the electron configuration [Ar] 3d10 (full d subshell) (1 mark). No d-d transitions are possible because there are no empty d orbitals for electrons to be promoted to, so no visible light is absorbed (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State what is meant by the standard electrode potential.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'The EMF/voltage of a half-cell (1 mark) measured relative to the standard hydrogen electrode (1 mark) under standard conditions (298 K, 100 kPa, 1 mol dm^-3 solutions) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Calculate the cell EMF for a cell with Cu^2+/Cu (E = +0.34 V) and Fe^2+/Fe (E = -0.44 V). Identify the positive terminal.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'EMF = +0.34 - (-0.44) = +0.78 V (1 mark). The copper electrode is the positive terminal (cathode) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why Fe^3+ can act as an oxidising agent.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Fe^3+ has a relatively high positive electrode potential for the Fe^3+/Fe^2+ half-cell (+0.77 V) (1 mark). This means Fe^3+ readily accepts electrons (is reduced) to become Fe^2+, oxidising the other species (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe the colour changes observed when vanadium is reduced from V^5+ to V^2+.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'V^5+ is yellow, V^4+ is blue, V^3+ is green (1 mark). V^2+ is violet/lilac (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by a ligand substitution reaction. Give an example.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'A ligand substitution reaction is one where one ligand in a complex is replaced by another ligand (1 mark). The coordination number may or may not change (1 mark). Example: [Cu(H2O)6]^2+ + 4Cl^- -> [CuCl4]^2- + 6H2O (blue to yellow/green) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State the shape and bond angle of a tetrahedral complex. Give an example.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Tetrahedral shape with bond angles of 109.5 degrees (1 mark). Example: [CuCl4]^2- or [CoCl4]^2- (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by the chelate effect.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'The chelate effect is the enhanced stability of complexes containing polydentate/multidentate ligands compared to those with equivalent monodentate ligands (1 mark). When polydentate ligands replace monodentate ligands, the number of free particles increases (1 mark). This increase in entropy makes the reaction more thermodynamically favourable (delta G more negative) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe how to set up a standard hydrogen electrode.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Platinum electrode coated in platinum black (platinised) dipping into 1 mol dm^-3 HCl / H+ solution (1 mark). Hydrogen gas bubbled over the electrode at 100 kPa pressure (1 mark). Temperature maintained at 298 K (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'In the Contact process, V2O5 acts as a catalyst. Explain how it functions.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'V2O5 oxidises SO2 to SO3: SO2 + V2O5 -> SO3 + V2O4 (V reduced from +5 to +4) (1 mark). The reduced V2O4 is then re-oxidised by O2: 2V2O4 + O2 -> 2V2O5 (V oxidised back to +5) (1 mark). The catalyst cycles between +5 and +4 oxidation states, demonstrating variable oxidation states (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'What is a fuel cell? State one advantage over conventional batteries.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A fuel cell converts chemical energy directly into electrical energy using a continuous supply of fuel (e.g., hydrogen) and oxygen (1 mark). Advantage: higher efficiency than combustion, or produces only water as a by-product (for H2 fuel cells), or continuous supply of electricity as long as fuel is provided (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why a positive cell EMF indicates a feasible reaction.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A positive EMF means delta G is negative (since delta G = -nFE) (1 mark). A negative delta G means the reaction is thermodynamically spontaneous/feasible (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Write the electron configuration of Cu^2+ and explain why copper is a transition metal.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Cu^2+ is [Ar] 3d9 (1 mark). Copper is a transition metal because Cu^2+ has an incomplete d subshell (3d9) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State the colours of the following aqueous ions: Cu^2+, Fe^2+, Fe^3+, Cr^3+.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Cu^2+ is blue, Fe^2+ is green (1 mark). Fe^3+ is yellow/brown, Cr^3+ is green/violet (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why EDTA is particularly effective as a ligand.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'EDTA is a hexadentate ligand with six lone pairs that can form coordinate bonds to a metal ion (1 mark). It forms very stable complexes due to the chelate effect (1 mark). When EDTA replaces 6 monodentate ligands, the number of free particles increases from 1 to 6, giving a large positive entropy change (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe the test for Fe^2+ and Fe^3+ ions using NaOH(aq).', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Fe^2+ with NaOH(aq) gives a green precipitate of Fe(OH)2 (which darkens on standing in air as it oxidises) (1 mark). Fe^3+ with NaOH(aq) gives a brown/rust-coloured precipitate of Fe(OH)3 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why the reaction between MnO4^- and Fe^2+ must be carried out in acid solution.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'H+ ions are needed as they appear in the balanced equation: MnO4^- + 8H+ + 5Fe^2+ -> Mn^2+ + 5Fe^3+ + 4H2O (1 mark). Without acid, MnO2 (brown solid) would form instead of the Mn^2+ (colourless), making the end point difficult to observe (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'What is meant by a bidentate ligand? Give two examples.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A bidentate ligand has two lone pairs that can each form a coordinate bond to the metal ion (it bonds through two donor atoms) (1 mark). Examples: ethane-1,2-diamine (en), ethanedioate (C2O4^2-), or 1,2-diaminoethane (1 mark for two correct examples).' },
      { q: 'Describe and explain the observation when NH3(aq) is added dropwise to CuSO4(aq) until in excess.', marks: 4, markScheme: 'Initially a pale blue precipitate of Cu(OH)2 forms (1 mark). The OH^- from the NH3(aq) reacts with Cu^2+: Cu^2+(aq) + 2OH^-(aq) -> Cu(OH)2(s) (1 mark). With excess NH3, the precipitate dissolves to form a deep blue solution (1 mark). Ligand substitution occurs: Cu(OH)2 + 4NH3 -> [Cu(NH3)4(H2O)2]^2+ + 2OH^- (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why standard electrode potential data may not always predict whether a reaction actually occurs.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Electrode potentials predict thermodynamic feasibility only (whether a reaction is energetically possible) (1 mark). They give no information about the rate/kinetics of the reaction (1 mark). A reaction may have a high activation energy barrier making it too slow to observe even though it is thermodynamically feasible (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Define the term disproportionation and give one example involving a transition metal.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Disproportionation is when a species is simultaneously oxidised and reduced in the same reaction (1 mark). Example: 2Cu+(aq) -> Cu(s) + Cu^2+(aq) (1 mark). Cu+ (oxidation state +1) is both oxidised to +2 and reduced to 0 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Calculate the oxidation state of nitrogen in NO3^-.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'N + 3(-2) = -1. N = -1 + 6 = +5 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State the shape and coordination number of [Cr(NH3)6]^3+.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Octahedral shape (1 mark). Coordination number = 6 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why transition metal compounds are often paramagnetic.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Transition metal ions often have unpaired electrons in their d orbitals (1 mark). These unpaired electrons give rise to paramagnetism, meaning the compounds are attracted to a magnetic field (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Write the half-equation for the oxidation of Fe^2+ to Fe^3+.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'Fe^2+ -> Fe^3+ + e^- (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain how a salt bridge works in an electrochemical cell.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The salt bridge (e.g., filter paper soaked in KNO3) allows ions to flow between the two half-cells (1 mark). This maintains electrical neutrality in each half-cell and completes the circuit (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'In a hydrogen-oxygen fuel cell, write the half-equation at the cathode.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'O2 + 4H+ + 4e^- -> 2H2O (in acid conditions) (1 mark for correct equation, 1 mark for correct balancing). Or in alkaline: O2 + 2H2O + 4e^- -> 4OH^-.' },
      { q: 'Explain what cis-trans isomerism is in coordination chemistry and give an example.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Cis-trans isomerism occurs in square planar or octahedral complexes where identical ligands can be adjacent (cis) or opposite (trans) to each other (1 mark). In cis isomers, two identical ligands are next to each other (90 degrees apart) (1 mark). Example: cis-platin [Pt(NH3)2Cl2] has cis and trans forms; the cis form is used as an anti-cancer drug (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe one industrial use of a transition metal as a catalyst, naming the metal and the process.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Iron is used as a catalyst in the Haber process for the manufacture of ammonia: N2 + 3H2 <=> 2NH3 (1 mark). Or: vanadium(V) oxide (V2O5) in the Contact process for manufacturing sulfuric acid, or nickel in hydrogenation of alkenes/vegetable oils, or platinum/palladium/rhodium in catalytic converters (1 mark for any correct example with metal and process named).' },
      { q: 'Calculate the number of moles of electrons transferred when 0.010 mol of Cu^2+ is reduced to Cu.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'Cu^2+ + 2e^- -> Cu. Moles of electrons = 2 x 0.010 = 0.020 mol (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why transition metals form complex ions.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Transition metal ions are small and have a high charge density (1 mark). They have vacant/available d orbitals that can accept lone pairs from ligands (1 mark). Ligands donate electron pairs to form coordinate/dative covalent bonds with the metal ion (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'What is the difference between a monodentate and a polydentate ligand?', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A monodentate ligand forms one coordinate bond with the metal ion (has one donor atom / one lone pair used for bonding) (1 mark). A polydentate ligand forms two or more coordinate bonds with the metal ion (has multiple donor atoms) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State three features of the standard hydrogen electrode (SHE).', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Platinum electrode (1 mark). 1 mol dm^-3 H+(aq) solution (1 mark). H2 gas at 100 kPa and 298 K (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Write a balanced equation for the reaction of Fe with dilute H2SO4, and identify what is oxidised and reduced.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Fe(s) + H2SO4(aq) -> FeSO4(aq) + H2(g) or Fe + 2H+ -> Fe^2+ + H2 (1 mark). Iron is oxidised (0 to +2) (1 mark). Hydrogen is reduced (+1 to 0) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why the stability constant (Kstab) for [Cu(NH3)4(H2O)2]^2+ is larger than for [Cu(H2O)6]^2+.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'NH3 is a stronger field ligand than H2O, forming stronger coordinate bonds with Cu^2+ (1 mark). The resulting complex is more thermodynamically stable, giving a larger Kstab value (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'What is the role of the platinum electrode in a hydrogen half-cell?', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Platinum provides an inert conducting surface for the half-reaction to occur (1 mark). It allows electron transfer without reacting itself, and it catalyses the equilibrium between H2 and H+ ions (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe one environmental benefit and one limitation of hydrogen fuel cells.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Benefit: The only product is water, so no pollutants (CO2, NOx, particulates) are released during operation (1 mark). Limitation: Hydrogen production often requires fossil fuels or electrolysis (energy-intensive), storage of H2 is difficult (flammable, low density), or infrastructure for hydrogen distribution is limited (any one for 1 mark).' }
    ]
  },
  'S6': {
    name: 'Advanced Organic Chemistry and Analysis',
    questions: [
      { q: 'Describe the Kekule model of benzene and explain one piece of evidence against it.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Kekule proposed benzene has alternating single and double C-C bonds in a hexagonal ring (1 mark). Evidence against: benzene does not undergo addition reactions readily as expected for C=C bonds (1 mark). Also, all C-C bond lengths in benzene are equal (0.139 nm), intermediate between single (0.154 nm) and double (0.134 nm) bonds, inconsistent with alternating bonds (1 mark). Or: the enthalpy of hydrogenation is less exothermic than expected for three C=C bonds.' },
      { q: 'State the conditions for the Friedel-Crafts acylation of benzene.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Acyl chloride (RCOCl) with an AlCl3 catalyst (1 mark). Heat under reflux in anhydrous conditions (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'What is a carbonyl compound? Name two types.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A carbonyl compound contains a C=O (carbonyl) functional group (1 mark). Two types: aldehydes (-CHO, carbonyl at end of chain) and ketones (-CO-, carbonyl between two carbon groups) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe how you would use 2,4-dinitrophenylhydrazine (2,4-DNPH) to test for a carbonyl compound.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Add 2,4-DNPH reagent (Brady\'s reagent) to the unknown compound (1 mark). A yellow/orange precipitate (hydrazone) forms if a carbonyl group (aldehyde or ketone) is present (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why aldehydes give a positive result with Tollens\' reagent but ketones do not.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Tollens\' reagent contains Ag+ ions in ammonia solution (1 mark). Aldehydes are easily oxidised to carboxylic acids, reducing Ag+ to Ag (silver mirror) (1 mark). Ketones cannot be oxidised by Tollens\' reagent because they lack the H atom on the carbonyl carbon needed for oxidation (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Name the organic product when ethanoyl chloride reacts with ethanol.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'Ethyl ethanoate (an ester) is formed, along with HCl (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'What is the difference between a primary, secondary, and tertiary amine?', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Primary amine: nitrogen bonded to one alkyl/aryl group and two hydrogen atoms (RNH2) (1 mark). Secondary amine: nitrogen bonded to two alkyl/aryl groups and one hydrogen (R2NH) (1 mark). Tertiary amine: nitrogen bonded to three alkyl/aryl groups and no hydrogens (R3N) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why amines are basic.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Amines have a lone pair of electrons on the nitrogen atom (1 mark). This lone pair can accept a proton (H+) from water or an acid, acting as a Bronsted-Lowry base: RNH2 + H+ -> RNH3+ (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Define the term amino acid. Draw the general structure.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'An amino acid is a molecule containing both an amine (-NH2) group and a carboxylic acid (-COOH) group (1 mark). General structure: H2N-CHR-COOH where R is a variable side chain (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe how a peptide bond is formed between two amino acids.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A condensation reaction occurs between the amine group of one amino acid and the carboxyl group of another (1 mark). Water is eliminated and a peptide bond (C(=O)-NH, an amide link) is formed (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'In mass spectrometry, a compound shows M+ at m/z = 46 and a fragment at m/z = 31. Suggest the identity of the compound and the fragment.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'M+ = 46 suggests ethanol (CH3CH2OH, Mr = 46) (1 mark). Fragment at 31 = 46 - 15 = loss of CH3 (1 mark). The fragment at m/z = 31 is CHO+ or CH2OH+ (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State what information is obtained from the chemical shift in an NMR spectrum.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The chemical shift (delta, in ppm) indicates the electronic environment of the hydrogen (or carbon) atoms (1 mark). Different functional groups and bonding environments give characteristic chemical shift ranges, allowing identification of the types of hydrogen/carbon present (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain the n+1 rule in ^1H NMR spectroscopy.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A peak in a ^1H NMR spectrum is split into (n+1) peaks, where n is the number of hydrogen atoms on adjacent (non-equivalent) carbon atoms (1 mark). For example, if a CH3 group is adjacent to a CH2, the CH3 peak appears as a triplet (2+1=3) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe the mechanism of nucleophilic addition of HCN to ethanal.', marks: 4, markScheme: 'The carbonyl carbon is delta+ due to the electronegativity of oxygen (1 mark). CN^- (nucleophile, from KCN) attacks the delta+ carbon; curly arrow from CN^- to C (1 mark). The pi bond in C=O breaks; curly arrow from C=O to O, forming an alkoxide intermediate (1 mark). The alkoxide is protonated by HCN: O^- + HCN -> OH + CN^-, forming 2-hydroxypropanenitrile (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain how gas chromatography works.', marks: 4, markScheme: 'A sample is vaporised and injected into a column (1 mark). An inert carrier gas (mobile phase) carries the sample through the column packed with a liquid/solid stationary phase (1 mark). Components separate based on their different affinities for the stationary phase (or different boiling points) (1 mark). Components exit at different retention times; a detector records each component as a peak on a chromatogram (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'What is the difference between addition polymerisation and condensation polymerisation?', marks: 4, markScheme: 'Addition polymerisation: unsaturated monomers (alkenes) join together by opening their double bonds (1 mark). No by-product is formed and the polymer has the same empirical formula as the monomer (1 mark). Condensation polymerisation: monomers with two functional groups join together with elimination of a small molecule (usually H2O) (1 mark). Examples include polyesters (from diols + dicarboxylic acids) and polyamides (from diamines + dicarboxylic acids) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'State the characteristic IR absorption frequencies for: (a) O-H in alcohol, (b) C=O, (c) O-H in carboxylic acid.', marks: 3, markScheme: '(a) O-H in alcohol: broad absorption at 3230-3550 cm^-1 (1 mark). (b) C=O: strong sharp absorption at 1680-1750 cm^-1 (1 mark). (c) O-H in carboxylic acid: very broad absorption at 2500-3300 cm^-1 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why benzene has a lower enthalpy of hydrogenation than expected for a molecule with three C=C double bonds.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'The expected enthalpy of hydrogenation for three isolated C=C bonds would be 3 x (-120) = -360 kJ/mol (1 mark). The actual enthalpy of hydrogenation of benzene is about -208 kJ/mol, which is 152 kJ/mol less exothermic (1 mark). This difference is the delocalisation/resonance energy, showing that benzene is more stable than the hypothetical cyclohexatriene due to electron delocalisation (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe how you would identify an unknown organic compound using IR spectroscopy and mass spectrometry together.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Use mass spectrometry to determine the molecular mass from the M+ peak and identify fragments to suggest the molecular formula (1 mark). Use IR spectroscopy to identify functional groups present from characteristic absorptions (e.g., O-H, C=O, N-H) (1 mark). Combine information from both techniques to narrow down the identity and confirm the structure (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Draw the repeating unit of a polyester formed from ethane-1,2-diol and benzene-1,4-dicarboxylic acid (terephthalic acid).', marks: 2, markScheme: 'The repeating unit shows -O-CH2-CH2-O-CO-C6H4-CO- with ester linkages (-COO-) (1 mark). Correct structure with continuation bonds at both ends and n notation (1 mark). This is PET (polyethylene terephthalate).' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by a chromophore in the context of azo dyes.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A chromophore is the part of a molecule responsible for its colour / the part that absorbs visible light (1 mark). In azo dyes, the -N=N- (azo) group is the chromophore; the extended conjugation/delocalisation across the azo group and aromatic rings absorbs specific wavelengths of visible light (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'What product forms when a Grignard reagent (CH3MgBr) reacts with methanal, followed by hydrolysis?', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Ethanol (CH3CH2OH) is formed (1 mark). The Grignard reagent adds to the C=O of methanal (HCHO), and hydrolysis with dilute acid gives a primary alcohol (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe one method for determining the structure of a protein (sequence of amino acids).', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Hydrolysis of the protein into individual amino acids using acid/enzymes (1 mark). Separation and identification using chromatography (paper, TLC, or HPLC) or mass spectrometry (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why carbon-13 NMR is useful even though ^13C is only 1.1% abundant.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Modern NMR spectrometers are sensitive enough to detect the low abundance ^13C nuclei (1 mark). ^13C NMR provides information about the number of different carbon environments in a molecule, which is complementary to ^1H NMR for structure determination (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe the observation when 2,4-DNPH is added to propanone.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'A yellow/orange precipitate forms, confirming the presence of a carbonyl group (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'How many peaks would you expect in the ^1H NMR spectrum of propanone (CH3COCH3)?', marks: 1, markScheme: 'One peak (singlet), because all six hydrogen atoms are in the same chemical environment (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe the mechanism of electrophilic substitution for the bromination of benzene.', marks: 5, markScheme: 'The electrophile Br+ is generated: Br2 + AlBr3 -> Br+ + AlBr4^- (1 mark). A curly arrow from the pi system of the benzene ring attacks the Br+ electrophile (1 mark). A Wheland intermediate (cyclohexadienyl cation) is formed with Br bonded and a positive charge delocalised over the ring (1 mark). A hydrogen is lost: curly arrow from C-H bond back into the ring (1 mark). AlBr4^- acts as a base, accepting H+ to regenerate AlBr3 and form HBr (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why acyl chlorides are more reactive than carboxylic acids in nucleophilic substitution reactions.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Acyl chlorides have a good leaving group (Cl^-) whereas in carboxylic acids, OH^- is a poor leaving group (1 mark). The electron-withdrawing Cl makes the carbonyl carbon more delta positive/electrophilic (1 mark). No catalyst is needed for acyl chloride reactions, and they occur rapidly at room temperature (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Name the product formed when ethanoic anhydride reacts with methylamine.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'N-methylethanamide (an amide) is formed (1 mark). The other product is ethanoic acid / CH3COOH (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by the term retention time in chromatography.', marks: 1, markScheme: 'Retention time is the time taken for a component to travel through the chromatography column from injection to detection (1 mark). Different substances have different retention times based on their interactions with the stationary phase.' },
      { q: 'Explain why optical isomers of amino acids are biologically important.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Most natural amino acids exist as only one enantiomer (L-form) (1 mark). Enzymes are chiral and their active sites can only bind one enantiomer (stereospecific) (1 mark). Using the wrong enantiomer would prevent proper protein folding and enzyme function (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe how a polyamide (e.g., nylon 6,6) is formed.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'Nylon 6,6 is formed from hexanedioic acid (a dicarboxylic acid) and 1,6-diaminohexane (a diamine) (1 mark). A condensation reaction occurs between the amine group of one monomer and the carboxyl group of the other (1 mark). Water is eliminated and amide/peptide bonds (-CONH-) form between the monomers (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'A compound has the molecular formula C3H6O. It does not react with 2,4-DNPH or Tollens\' reagent. Suggest its structure.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Since it does not react with 2,4-DNPH, it does not contain a carbonyl group (1 mark). Possible structures: propenol (prop-2-en-1-ol, CH2=CHCH2OH) or methoxyethene (CH2=CHOCH3) or oxacyclopropane (epoxide). An acceptable answer is an unsaturated alcohol or an ether (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe the fragmentation pattern expected in the mass spectrum of butan-1-ol (Mr = 74).', marks: 3, markScheme: 'M+ peak at m/z = 74 (1 mark). Loss of H2O (18) gives fragment at m/z = 56 (1 mark). Loss of CH2OH (31) from M+ gives fragment at m/z = 43 (C3H7+); or loss of C2H5 (29) gives m/z = 45 (CH2CH2OH+ or CHOH+) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by the term biodegradable polymer and give one example.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A biodegradable polymer is one that can be broken down by biological organisms (bacteria, fungi) into simpler molecules over time (1 mark). Example: polylactic acid (PLA), polyhydroxybutyrate (PHB), starch-based polymers, or proteins (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Why does phenol react with bromine water without a catalyst, whereas benzene requires an AlBr3 catalyst?', marks: 3, markScheme: 'The -OH group on phenol activates the ring by donating electron density from the oxygen lone pair into the pi system via delocalisation (1 mark). This increases the electron density of the ring, making it more reactive towards electrophiles (1 mark). Benzene has lower electron density without an activating group, so a Lewis acid catalyst (AlBr3) is needed to generate a stronger electrophile (Br+) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'In a ^1H NMR spectrum, a compound shows a quartet at delta 4.1 ppm and a triplet at delta 1.2 ppm. What structural feature does this suggest?', marks: 2, markScheme: 'This pattern is characteristic of an ethyl group (-OCH2CH3) adjacent to an electronegative atom like oxygen (1 mark). The quartet (4 peaks) is the CH2 split by 3 adjacent H atoms on CH3; the triplet (3 peaks) is the CH3 split by 2 adjacent H atoms on CH2 (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'What is the role of D2O in ^1H NMR spectroscopy?', marks: 2, markScheme: 'D2O (deuterium oxide) is added to exchange labile/acidic protons (O-H, N-H) with deuterium (1 mark). The peaks due to O-H or N-H protons disappear from the spectrum, helping to identify which peaks correspond to these groups (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between a polyester and a polyamide.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A polyester contains ester linkages (-COO-) formed from the reaction of dicarboxylic acids with diols (1 mark). A polyamide contains amide linkages (-CONH-) formed from the reaction of dicarboxylic acids with diamines (or from amino acids) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe how NMR spectroscopy can be used in medical imaging (MRI).', marks: 2, markScheme: 'MRI uses the principles of NMR to detect hydrogen atoms (^1H) in water molecules in the body (1 mark). Different tissues contain different amounts of water and produce different signals, allowing detailed images of soft tissues to be generated without ionising radiation (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by a directing group in aromatic chemistry. Give one example of a 2,4-directing group.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'A directing group is a substituent already on a benzene ring that determines the position at which the next electrophilic substitution occurs (1 mark). Example of a 2,4-directing (ortho/para) group: -OH, -NH2, -CH3, or any electron-donating group (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Calculate the degree of unsaturation (index of hydrogen deficiency) for C8H10O.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Formula: IHD = (2C + 2 + N - H) / 2 for CcHhNnOo (oxygen does not affect the calculation). IHD = (2(8) + 2 - 10) / 2 = (16 + 2 - 10) / 2 = 8/2 = 4 (1 mark). This suggests a benzene ring (4 degrees of unsaturation) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Describe the test for a primary amine using copper(II) sulfate and NaOH.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'This is the biuret test, but actually the specific test for primary amines is with nitrous acid (NaNO2 + HCl). Primary aliphatic amines react with nitrous acid to produce nitrogen gas (bubbles) and an alcohol (1 mark). Primary aromatic amines react below 10 degrees C to form diazonium salts (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'Explain why the C=O absorption in an IR spectrum of a conjugated carbonyl (e.g., benzaldehyde) appears at a lower wavenumber than in a non-conjugated carbonyl.', marks: 2, markScheme: 'Conjugation (delocalisation of electrons from the ring into the C=O) weakens the C=O bond slightly by spreading electron density (1 mark). A weaker bond vibrates at a lower frequency, so the absorption appears at a lower wavenumber (e.g., 1680-1700 cm^-1 instead of 1720-1740 cm^-1) (1 mark).' },
      { q: 'A compound C4H8O2 shows a singlet at delta 3.7 ppm (3H) and a singlet at delta 2.1 ppm (3H) in ^1H NMR, and a strong absorption at 1740 cm^-1 in IR. Identify the compound.', marks: 3, markScheme: 'The IR absorption at 1740 cm^-1 indicates a C=O in an ester (1 mark). The singlet at 3.7 ppm (3H) suggests -OCH3 (methoxy group) (1 mark). The singlet at 2.1 ppm (3H) suggests CH3CO-. The compound is methyl ethanoate (CH3COOCH3) (1 mark).' }
    ]
  }
};

if (typeof module !== 'undefined' && module.exports) {
  module.exports = { CHEMISTRY_OCR_B_PRACTICE };
}
